Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Jordan K Kelser in court with attorney Anne M Jaspers.  Catelin Ringersma appeared for the State of Wisconsin.


Sentencing proceeds.  Statements made by the state, defense counsel and defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1 (AMENDED TO A MISDEMEANOR):   Defendant sentenced to serve 9 months at the HOUSE OF CORRECTION with release privileges for the Day Reporting Center only. 
Credit for ZERO days time served. 

COURT STAYS sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for a period of 1 YEAR under the supervision of Wisconsin Department of Corrections.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION (AS TO COUNT 1, MISDEMEANOR): 
* Comply with the standard rules of probation.
* Complete a job training program to enhance ability to obtain employment.
* Cooperate and participate with a mental health evaluation and follow any recommended treatment.
* Cooperate and participate with an AODA assessment and follow any recommended treatment.
* Maintain absolute sobriety and submit to random urine screens.
* PAY DNA surcharge - to be paid over a period of probation.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.
* PAY the balance of all applicable court costs, fees, and surcharges - to be paid over a period of probation.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.

OTHER COURT ORDERS:
* Court will grant a petition for expundgement if defendant successfully completes probation without any violations AND pays all court costs, fees, surcharges, and restitution in full.
* Restitution to be determined at an upcoming restitution hearing - to be paid over a period of probation.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.

  ALL PARTIES ARE NOTIFIED AS OF AUGUST 1, 2015, THIS CASE WILL BE REASSIGNED TO JUDGE JEFFREY CONEN, BRANCH 30, IN ROOM 635 OF THE COURTHOUSE, DUE TO JUDICIAL ROTATION.

Upon State's motion and pursuant to negotiations, Court ordered Count #1 AMENDED to:  Misdemeanor Theft (a Value < $2500) [a Class A MISDEMEANOR], contrary to Wisc. Stats. Sec. 943.20(1)(a) and (3)(a).

**NO AMENDED INFORMATION FILED.

AS TO COUNT 1 (MISDEMEANOR):    Defendant changes his plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.   Defendant advised that if not a United States Citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found that defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant guilty and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.
